---
import HubLayout from '../layouts/HubLayout.astro';
import PeptideCard from '../components/PeptideCard.astro';
import { getCollection } from 'astro:content';

const allPeptides = await getCollection('peptides');
const bioregulatorPeptides = allPeptides
  .filter(p => p.data.bioregulatorType)
  .sort((a, b) => a.data.name.localeCompare(b.data.name));

const syntheticPeptides = bioregulatorPeptides.filter(p => p.data.bioregulatorType === 'synthetic');
const extractPeptides = bioregulatorPeptides.filter(p => p.data.bioregulatorType === 'extract');
const cytaminPeptides = bioregulatorPeptides.filter(p => p.data.bioregulatorType === 'cytamin');
---

<HubLayout
  title="Bioregulator Peptides"
  description="Khavinson bioregulators: Russian peptide bioregulation research. Evidence dossiers on epithalon, thymalin, cortexin, and synthetic tripeptides."
  category="longevity"
>
  <div class="mb-12">
    <p class="text-lg text-[color:var(--ink-muted)] max-w-3xl leading-relaxed mb-6">
      Bioregulator peptides are short peptides developed primarily by Russian scientist Vladimir Khavinson
      and colleagues at the St. Petersburg Institute of Bioregulation and Gerontology. These compounds
      are claimed to regulate gene expression in specific tissues through epigenetic mechanisms.
    </p>

    <div class="glass-card-amber p-6 rounded-xl">
      <p class="text-sm" style="color: #9a6418;">
        <strong style="color: #9a6418;">Evidence Note:</strong> Most bioregulator research originates from
        a single Russian institute with limited independent Western validation. Evidence quality for most
        compounds is very low. The 2025 UK replication of epithalon's telomerase effects was the first
        significant independent confirmation.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl mb-6" style="font-family: var(--font-serif); font-weight: 500; color: var(--ink);">Synthetic Bioregulators</h2>
    <p class="text-[color:var(--ink-muted)] mb-6">
      Defined amino acid sequences synthesized to mimic tissue-specific peptide signals.
    </p>
    {syntheticPeptides.length > 0 ? (
      <div class="grid gap-6 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3">
        {syntheticPeptides.map((peptide) => (
          <PeptideCard
            name={peptide.data.name}
            slug={peptide.slug}
            category={peptide.data.category}
            evidenceStrength={peptide.data.evidenceStrength}
            summary={peptide.data.summary}
            aliases={peptide.data.aliases}
          />
        ))}
      </div>
    ) : (
      <p class="text-[color:var(--ink-dim)]">No synthetic bioregulators found.</p>
    )}
  </div>

  {extractPeptides.length > 0 && (
    <div class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl mb-6" style="font-family: var(--font-serif); font-weight: 500; color: var(--ink);">Tissue Extract Complexes</h2>
      <p class="text-[color:var(--ink-muted)] mb-6">
        Peptide mixtures extracted from animal tissues rather than synthesized. These are not single
        defined compounds but complex mixtures.
      </p>
      <div class="grid gap-6 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3">
        {extractPeptides.map((peptide) => (
          <PeptideCard
            name={peptide.data.name}
            slug={peptide.slug}
            category={peptide.data.category}
            evidenceStrength={peptide.data.evidenceStrength}
            summary={peptide.data.summary}
            aliases={peptide.data.aliases}
          />
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  )}

  {cytaminPeptides.length > 0 && (
    <div class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl mb-6" style="font-family: var(--font-serif); font-weight: 500; color: var(--ink);">Cytamin Supplements</h2>
      <p class="text-[color:var(--ink-muted)] mb-6">
        Oral peptide supplements derived from tissue extracts, marketed as dietary supplements in Russia.
        Cytamins contain multiple peptide fractions rather than single defined sequences. Oral bioavailability
        of peptides is generally very low.
      </p>
      <div class="grid gap-6 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3">
        {cytaminPeptides.map((peptide) => (
          <PeptideCard
            name={peptide.data.name}
            slug={peptide.slug}
            category={peptide.data.category}
            evidenceStrength={peptide.data.evidenceStrength}
            summary={peptide.data.summary}
            aliases={peptide.data.aliases}
          />
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  )}

  <div class="mt-16 glass-card-default p-8">
    <h3 class="mb-4 text-lg" style="font-family: var(--font-serif); font-weight: 500; color: var(--ink);">About Bioregulator Research</h3>
    <div class="prose prose-invert prose-sm max-w-none text-[color:var(--ink-muted)]">
      <p>
        The bioregulation theory proposes that short peptides (2-4 amino acids) can selectively
        regulate gene expression in specific tissues by interacting with DNA and chromatin.
        Khavinson's research claims these peptides can "normalize" tissue function and reverse
        age-related changes.
      </p>
      <p>
        While intriguing, these claims require significant further validation. The proposed
        mechanisms—that a simple dipeptide like KE (Vilon) can selectively target thymus tissue
        while EDG (Kristagen) targets immune cells and the same EDG sequence in Chonluten targets
        the GI tract—lack a clear scientific explanation for tissue specificity.
      </p>
      <p>
        Consumers should understand that most bioregulators have very low evidence quality,
        are not approved by any Western regulatory agency, and claims are based primarily on
        Russian research that has not been independently replicated.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

